<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="514" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,253,2021]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,577,602]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[354,458,577,602]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete, 
<quantity box="[588,676,577,601]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[753,842,577,601]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
wide, 34 chaetigers. Body small, long and slender, preserved specimens without a distinctive color pattern (
<figureCitation box="[804,874,612,637]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Dorsum and parapodia with a few, short and digitiform papillae, more abundant on the sides of the segments (
<figureCitation box="[882,950,648,673]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Prostomium ovate to trapezoidal, wider than long, with two pairs of large eyes in trapezoidal arrangement; very close to each other; posterior pair partially covered by the peristomium, eyespots absent (
<figureCitation box="[707,780,719,744]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Antennae short, not exceeding the length of palps, piriform, with bulbous bases and slender tips; median antenna originating posteriorly on prostomium; lateral pair arising on anterior margin of prostomium, between posterior pair of eyes (
<figureCitation box="[1013,1088,790,815]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
A, 5A). Palps wide, similar in length to prostomium, completely fused, with a well-marked union groove (
<figureCitation box="[1054,1131,825,850]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
A, 5A). Peristomium well defined, similar in size to following segments, extending forward to form a cephalic hood which covers the posterior half of the prostomium (
<figureCitation box="[531,598,896,921]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A); tentacular cirri similar in form and size to antennae, located laterally at the level of anterior eyes. Antennae, tentacular and dorsal cirri similar in shape, short, with bases distinctly globular to ovate, with slender tips and containing granular material (
<figureCitation box="[856,931,967,992]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
A, 5A). Each segment with four transversal annuli: first one very narrow compared to the other three, flanking the anterior segment; second, third and fourth similar in size and at least twice as wide as first one. The third carries parapodial lobes (
<figureCitation box="[1190,1260,1038,1063]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1674,1696]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,199,1642]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,193,1653]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. SEM micrographs of Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view. (B) Detail of the dorsum (Roman numerals indicate the annuli of chaetigers). (C) Anterior chaetae. (D) Posterior chaetae. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Dorsal simple chaeta. Scale: A, B = 20 µm; C, D, F = 5 µm; E = 2 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259837/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
B). Dorsal cirri present in all segments, similar in size and shape to antennae, not extending beyond parapodial lobes (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1402,1073,1098]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1674,1696]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,199,1642]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,193,1653]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. SEM micrographs of Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view. (B) Detail of the dorsum (Roman numerals indicate the annuli of chaetigers). (C) Anterior chaetae. (D) Posterior chaetae. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Dorsal simple chaeta. Scale: A, B = 20 µm; C, D, F = 5 µm; E = 2 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259837/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
B). Ventral cirri short, digitiform, arising roughly in the middle region of parapodial lobes, not extending beyond their length. Parapodial lobes short, conical, distally rounded, with papillae on lateral margins. Parapodial glands small, rounded, containing granular material, present from chaetigers 5 to 15, more conspicuous on anterior chaetigers (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,1215,1240]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Four or five heterogomph compound chaetae per anterior parapodium (
<figureCitation box="[1090,1165,1215,1240]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
B, 5C), three chaetae in middle parapodia and two in posterior ones (sometimes three) (
<figureCitation box="[921,999,1251,1276]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
C, 5D). Chaetae with short, hooked, unidentate blades (
<figureCitation box="[371,449,1286,1311]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
B, C, 5C, D). Well-marked dorso-ventral gradation in blade length; antero-posterior gradation in size barely marked. Superior falcigers of anterior region with 8–9 coarse and long spines that gradually diminish in length towards the distal end; ventral falcigers smooth or with few spines on basal margin, similar to those present on posterior region (
<figureCitation box="[556,628,1393,1418]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
B). One dorsal simple chaeta per parapodium from second chaetiger, unidentate, smooth, subdistally curved (
<figureCitation box="[600,672,1428,1453]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Figs 4</figureCitation>
E, 5E). One ventral simple chaeta on posterior chaetigers, similar in shape to dorsal one but thinner (
<figureCitation box="[545,618,1463,1488]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
F). One acicula per parapodium, stout, distally bent at a right angle, subdistally slightly curved, with acuminate tip and oriented upwards (
<figureCitation box="[958,1029,1499,1524]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
D). Pharynx extending through 3–4 segments, with a small and conical tooth on anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[872,943,1534,1559]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Proventricle short and wide, extending through two segments, with about 12–13 muscle cell rows (
<figureCitation box="[828,897,1570,1595]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,490,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[178,1402,476,1902]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Sphaerosyllis tetralobata n. sp. (A) Anterior end, dorsal view (arrows indicate parapodial glands). (B) Anterior chaetae. (C) Posterior chaetae. (D) Posterior acicula. (E) Dorsal simple chaeta. (F) Ventral simple chaeta. Scale: 40 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259836/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A). Pygidium rounded, with numerous papillae, two anal cirri similar to dorsal cirri, but thinner and longer, about twice their length and with a small digitiform appendix in the middle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="515" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,253,2021]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,425]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="515" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1676,1701]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[327,614,1677,1701]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetralobata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[327,614,1677,1701]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Sphaerosyllis tetralobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[625,693,1676,1701]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[625,693,1676,1701]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is characterized by having segments divided in four annuli of different sizes and hooked unidentate compound chaetae. 
<taxonomicName authority="Hartmann-Schroder 1962" authorityName="Hartmann-Schroder" authorityYear="1962" box="[832,1384,1712,1737]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dubiosa">
<emphasis box="[832,1082,1712,1736]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Sphaerosyllis dubiosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hartmann-Schroder" box="[1094,1384,1712,1737]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" refString="Hartmann-Schroder, G. (1962) Zur Kenntnis des Eulitorals der chilenischen Pazifikkuste und der argenstinischen Kuste Sudpatagoniens unter besonderer Berucksichtigung der Polychaeten und Ostracoden. Die Polychaeten der Eulitorals. Mitteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Zoologischen Museum und Institut, 60, 57 - 169." type="journal article" year="1962">Hartmann-Schröder 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="de Matos, San Martin &amp; Veronesi, 2004" authorityName="de Matos, San Martin &amp; Veronesi" authorityYear="2004" box="[151,903,1747,1772]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis box="[151,413,1748,1772]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">Sphaerosyllis annulata</emphasis>
de 
<bibRefCitation author="Matos" box="[464,903,1747,1772]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" refString="de Matos, J. M., San Martin, G. &amp; Veronesi, M. (2004) On some exogonines (Polychaeta, Syllidae, Exogoninae) from the northern coast of the State of Sao Paulo, southeastern Brazil. Results of BIOTA / FAPESP / Bentos Marinho Project. Meiofauna Marina, 13, 45 - 47." type="journal article" year="2004">Matos, San Martín &amp; Veronesi, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
are the two other species of the genus with segments clearly divided in annuli and the latter has the same pattern as 
<taxonomicName box="[962,1115,1783,1807]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetralobata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[962,1115,1783,1807]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. tetralobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1122,1185,1783,1808]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1122,1185,1783,1808]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1308,1436,1783,1807]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis box="[1308,1436,1783,1807]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks smooth falcigers and has no dorso-ventral gradation in blade length. Additionally, in 
<taxonomicName box="[1181,1310,1819,1843]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis box="[1181,1310,1819,1843]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
an oblique acicula protrudes from the parapodial lobes in posterior chaetigers, while 
<taxonomicName box="[1019,1176,1854,1878]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetralobata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1019,1176,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. tetralobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1187,1254,1854,1879]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1187,1254,1854,1879]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has the typical aciculae of the genus, distally bent at right angle and completely embedded in the parapodial lobes. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1308,1436,1889,1913]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis box="[1308,1436,1889,1913]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
parapodial glands are present along the whole body (more evident in the middle region), while in 
<taxonomicName box="[1253,1406,1925,1949]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetralobata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1253,1406,1925,1949]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">S. tetralobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="7" pageNumber="514" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
they are present in the anterior half of the body only and are more conspicuous in anterior segments. However, according to de 
<bibRefCitation box="[332,551,1996,2020]" pageId="7" pageNumber="514" refString="de Matos, J. M., San Martin, G. &amp; Veronesi, M. (2004) On some exogonines (Polychaeta, Syllidae, Exogoninae) from the northern coast of the State of Sao Paulo, southeastern Brazil. Results of BIOTA / FAPESP / Bentos Marinho Project. Meiofauna Marina, 13, 45 - 47." type="journal article">
Matos 
<emphasis box="[410,460,1996,2020]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="514">et al</emphasis>
. (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
, the distribution of the glands can vary with the physiological condition of the specimens, meaning that the glands’ activity could be affected during sampling and before the fixation of the organisms. On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName box="[511,632,187,211]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dubiosa">
<emphasis box="[511,632,187,211]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">S. dubiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the new species in having a characteristic color pattern, straight aciculae, palps distally separated and lacking parapodial glands (
<bibRefCitation author="Hartman-Schroder" box="[985,1265,222,247]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" refString="Hartmann-Schroder, G. (1962) Zur Kenntnis des Eulitorals der chilenischen Pazifikkuste und der argenstinischen Kuste Sudpatagoniens unter besonderer Berucksichtigung der Polychaeten und Ostracoden. Die Polychaeten der Eulitorals. Mitteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Zoologischen Museum und Institut, 60, 57 - 169." type="journal article" year="1962">Hartman-Schröder 1962</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[1286,1436,223,247]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1286,1436,223,247]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">Sphaerosyllis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<bibRefCitation author="San" box="[189,377,259,283]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" refString="San Martin, G. (2003) Annelida Polychaeta II: Syllidae. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, CSIC, Madrid, 554 pp." type="book" year="2003">San Martín 2003</bibRefCitation>
has a transversal striation in each segment, which constitutes a similar pattern to that observed in 
<taxonomicName box="[182,436,294,318]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Odontosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="alternata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[182,436,294,318]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">Odontosyllis alternata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[444,508,293,318]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[444,502,293,318]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, as described. However, this species has a slender and elongate proventricle and little gradation in blade length. Additionally, in some specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[921,1075,329,353]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetralobata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[921,1075,329,353]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">S. tetralobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1084,1155,329,354]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1084,1150,329,354]" pageId="8" pageNumber="515" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
there are some irregular pigmented areas extending from the eyes to the anterior margin of the peristomium, apparently due to the rupture of the pigment containers of the eyes and their spreading, a fact not observed in the other species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
